data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The temporary compatibility flag you configured in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — there is no workaround.

### The fix: migrate to async APIs

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return `Task<T>` / `Task` and mark methods `async`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

Note that `async` will propagate up your call chain — controllers, services, etc. must also become async. This is intentional; the Cosmos SDK is inherently async, and sync-over-async was always a deadlock risk.
